00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:37.730
We are also, our solar system
is filled with particles

00:46:37.730 --> 00:46:41.290
from outside the solar
system called cosmic rays.

00:46:41.290 --> 00:46:43.480
So, huge explosions that happen

00:46:43.480 --> 00:46:47.390
around the galaxy called
supernova; stars exploding.

00:46:47.390 --> 00:46:50.620
They treated particles even
more energetic than this.

00:46:50.620 --> 00:46:53.390
They're incredibly
powerful explosions.

00:46:53.390 --> 00:46:57.900 position:56%
And so, those particles are
everywhere and they actually make it

00:46:57.900 --> 00:47:01.380
into the solar system through
the magnetic field of the sun.

00:47:01.380 --> 00:47:04.690
But they are somewhat
deflected by that.

00:47:04.690 --> 00:47:07.040
So, when the sun is really active,

00:47:07.040 --> 00:47:10.060
these cosmic rays are
actually less of them.

00:47:10.060 --> 00:47:11.610
The sun actually pushes so when

00:47:11.610 --> 00:47:15.250
that heliosphere I
showed you pushes outward,

00:47:15.250 --> 00:47:20.030 position:56%
it actually pushes these cosmic rays
out and away from the solar system.

00:47:20.030 --> 00:47:22.380
And as the sun gets quieter,

00:47:22.380 --> 00:47:26.020
and that heliosphere shrinks,
more cosmic rays get in.

00:47:26.020 --> 00:47:30.970
So, when solar activity is
low, cosmic rays are high.

00:47:30.970 --> 00:47:35.430
And we actually see, if you look
at the sunspots, and cosmic rays,

00:47:35.430 --> 00:47:38.590 position:56%
they're exactly opposite each other.

00:47:38.590 --> 00:47:41.340
So, that's the other challenge.

00:47:41.340 --> 00:47:43.630
That I'm not going to talk
about in any detail here,

00:47:43.630 --> 00:47:45.960
but that's the other
part of traveling.

00:47:45.960 --> 00:47:48.040
It actually may turn
out, strangely enough

00:47:48.040 --> 00:47:52.110
that traveling during high
solar activity may be better

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:53.410
in the long run.

00:47:53.410 --> 00:47:56.840
Because it's really the long-term
exposure that's the issue.

00:47:56.840 --> 00:47:58.520
But, these are still a problem.

00:47:58.520 --> 00:48:02.000
The other part of this, you see
all those particles are hitting the

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:06.790
telescope and leaving
all this snow in there.

00:48:06.790 --> 00:48:10.780
Well, those particles also do the
same kind of thing to electronics.

00:48:10.780 --> 00:48:12.970
They're traveling through memory.

00:48:12.970 --> 00:48:17.340
So, one of the biggest issues is
when one of those particles travels

00:48:17.340 --> 00:48:20.300
through a piece of
memory, solid-state memory.

00:48:20.300 --> 00:48:25.270
So, remember we work in what's
called binary; zeros and ones.

00:48:25.270 --> 00:48:29.680 position:56%
All of our computers are using
zeros and ones to carry information.

00:48:29.680 --> 00:48:33.030
And if one of those
particles travels through,

00:48:33.030 --> 00:48:36.280
if it has enough energy,
it can actually flip.

00:48:36.280 --> 00:48:40.210
Turn a zero into a one,
or a one into a zero.

00:48:40.210 --> 00:48:43.770
You've got a whole bunch of
those, they make up an instruction

00:48:43.770 --> 00:48:47.060
that tells the telescope,
take a picture.

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:49.430
Stay on. Turn off.

00:48:49.430 --> 00:48:52.330
Or tells the spacecraft,
keep going forward.

00:48:52.330 --> 00:48:53.720
Go to the left, go to the right.

00:48:53.720 --> 00:48:57.610
There are all these commands
inside the computer that are made

00:48:57.610 --> 00:48:59.310
up of these zeros and ones.

00:48:59.310 --> 00:49:03.660
You've got this command and all of
the sudden a zero changes to a one.

00:49:03.660 --> 00:49:08.840 position:56%
The spacecraft has all the sudden
been told, oh turn off your engines.

00:49:08.840 --> 00:49:11.840
You know, shut off life
support, or something like that.

00:49:11.840 --> 00:49:14.410
I mean. So fortunately,
it's not quite,

00:49:14.410 --> 00:49:15.710
it's a little more
complicated that than.

00:49:15.710 --> 00:49:17.050
But that is a problem.

00:49:17.050 --> 00:49:20.060
So, this is the other
challenge when we go

00:49:20.060 --> 00:49:23.850
out into this harsh environment,
is that we have to deal with this.

00:49:23.850 --> 00:49:25.740
And so, we have to do
all kinds of things,

00:49:25.740 --> 00:49:28.330
like use software to
make corrections.

00:49:28.330 --> 00:49:31.440 position:56%
But when there's a really big storm,
one of the things we have to do

00:49:31.440 --> 00:49:33.880
for our spacecraft, is we
actually turn them off.

00:49:33.880 --> 00:49:36.300
We basically put them
in a safe mode.

00:49:36.300 --> 00:49:38.490
It's sort of like, there's
a thunderstorm coming,

00:49:38.490 --> 00:49:42.200
there's lightening, so you unplug
your stereo, or your TV so that

00:49:42.200 --> 00:49:45.290
if lightening hits it
doesn't kind of overload it.

00:49:45.290 --> 00:49:47.770
We sort of do something
similar to that.

00:49:47.770 --> 00:49:49.830
Basically, we put them
in a safe mode

00:49:49.830 --> 00:49:52.730
so that these things
don't have an impact.

